i minority. Yitzhak Nakash challenges the widely held belief that Shi'i society and politics in Iraq are a reflection of Iranian Shi'ism, pointing to the strong Arab attributes of Iraqi Shi'ism. He contends that behind the power struggle in Iraq between Arab Sunnis and Shi'is there exist two sectarian groups that are quite similar. The tension fueling the sectarian problem between Sunnis and Shi'is is political rather than ethnic or cultural, and it reflects the competition of the two groups over the right to rule and to define the meaning of nationalism in Iraq. A new introduction brings this book into the new century and illuminates the role that Shi`is could play in postwar Iraq.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aShiiteszIraqxHistory. 0aShīʿahzIraq. 0aShīʻahzIraq. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a'Adud al-Dawla.  aAbdul-Muttalib.  aAbu al-Faraj al-Isfahani.  aAbu al-Qasim.  aAhl al-Bayt.  aAhmad Kasravi.  aAl-Amin.  aAl-Dawla.  aAl-Ghadir.  aAl-Hadi.  aAl-Hayat.  aAl-Hilli.  aAl-Mahdi.  aAl-Mu'tamid.  aAl-Mulk.  aAl-Nasir.  aAl-Qaeda.  aAl-Qassab.  aAl-Shahrastani.  aAl-Shaykh Al-Mufid.  aAl-Tusi.  aAli Al-Wardi.  aAli al-Ridha.  aAmin al-Husseini.  aAnglo-Iraqi Treaty.  aBani Malik (tribe).  aBektashi Order.  aCaliphate.  aEmir.  aFakhr al-Din.  aHafez.  aHajji.  aHamid Algar.  aHashim.  aHikmat Sulayman.  aHusayn ibn Ali.  aHussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca.  aHussein.  aIbn Babawayh.  aInsurgency.  aIranian Revolution.  aIraq.  aIraqi Army.  aIraqi Communist Party.  aIraqi nationalism.  aIraqis in Iran.  aIraqis.  aIslam in Iraq.  aIslam.  aIslamic party.  aJa'far al-Sadiq.  aJa'far.  aJamal ad-Din al-Afghani.  aKarbala.  aKing of Syria.  aKurdistan.  aKurds in Iraq.  aKuwait.  